TreeSet in Java

TreeSet is a class in Java that implements the Set interface.

It stores unique elements like HashSet, but keeps them sorted.

How TreeSet works

TreeSet is based on a Red-Black Tree (self-balancing binary search tree).

👉 This means:

elements are always sorted
no duplicates allowed
Key Features
stores unique elements
elements are sorted
does NOT allow null ❌
not thread-safe
slower than HashSet
Creating a TreeSet
import java.util.TreeSet;
import java.util.Set;

Set<String> set = new TreeSet<>();
Example
set.add("Banana");
set.add("Apple");
set.add("Orange");

System.out.println(set);

👉 Output:

[Apple, Banana, Orange]
Sorting Rules
Default (Natural Order)
numbers → ascending
strings → alphabetical
Custom Sorting (Comparator)
Set<String> set = new TreeSet<>(
    (a, b) -> b.compareTo(a)
);

👉 reverse order

Common Methods
set.add("Apple");
set.remove("Apple");
set.contains("Apple");
set.size();
Navigational Methods
set.first();
set.last();

set.higher("Apple");  // next element
set.lower("Apple");   // previous element
Performance
Operation	Complexity
add()	O(log n)
remove()	O(log n)
contains()	O(log n)
TreeSet vs HashSet
Feature	TreeSet	HashSet
Order	Sorted	No order
Speed	O(log n)	O(1)
Null	❌	✅ (one)
When to use TreeSet

Use it when:

you need sorted unique elements
you need range operations
order matters
When NOT to use
when performance is critical → use HashSet
when sorting is not needed
Summary
TreeSet stores sorted unique elements
based on Red-Black Tree
slower than HashSet
useful when order matters
